5000|$|French {{language}} uses angle {{quotation marks}} (guillemets, or duck-foot quotes), adding a quarter-em space (officially) (...) within the quotes. However, many people now use the <b>non-breaking</b> <b>space,</b> because {{the difference between}} a <b>non-breaking</b> <b>space</b> and a four-per-em is virtually imperceptible (but also because the Unicode quarter-em space is breakable), and the quarter-em is virtually always omitted in non-Unicode fonts. Even more commonly, people just put a normal (breaking) space between the quotation marks because the <b>non-breaking</b> <b>space</b> is often not easily accessible from the keyboard.|$|E
